    <period>
     <period-start iso-date="2021-01-01"></period-start>
     <period-end iso-date="2021-12-31"></period-end>
     <target>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">1. Increasing the Institutional Capacity of MAEFP and MEF in Digital Connectivity
2. Strengthening Local Response Capacities: Digital solutions, Volunteers, Municipality services</narrative>
      </comment>
     </target>
     <actual>
      <comment>
       <narrative xml:lang="EN">-Operationalization of the Local Governance Response Situation Room in the Ministers Office of MAEFP
-Digital data platform developed and operating
UNDP supports MAEFP and MEF in enabling communication and continuity of operations. The integrated solution of tablets, Zoom licenses and 4G WIFI modems has already enabled 750 employees of these two ministries across the country and all levels of government to connect with each other and with counterparts inside and outside government,
- The development of a digital data platform to support the leadership of MAEFP and MEF, namely:
o MEF - An app that 1) monitors employee health and 2) functions as a time book to monitor employee sign-in and sign-out. 	
o MAEFP - An application that 1) identifies employees affected by COVID and 2) identifies the rules implemented in each Ministry or province. 
o A user manual for each application has been provided,
- Establishment of a partnership with ANAMM and the Eduardo Mondlane University that allowed the development of digital solutions and mechanisms for the effective, relevant and timely delivery of public services in the different beneficiaries. Through this partnership a Hackathon was developed, where an application to connect buyers and informal producers of agricultural products was developed (for the Municipal Council of Maputo City), and 3 digital solutions, namely: payment solution for certain municipal taxes and fees (for the Municipal Council of Boane Village). The partnership with UEM also resulted in the Volunteer Initiative where 2 students supported MEF with the digitization process (including training of staff in the use of Zoom), and
- Low value agreements with United Purpose and VSO
o Through engagement with United Purpose (UP), support was provided to the Ministry of State Administration and Public Services (MAEFP) and the Ministry of Economy and Finance (MEF), as well as municipalities. UPs work resulted in the empowerment of municipalities in the frontline management of the COVID-19 pandemic and the creation of a structured and organized crisis response and risk mitigation system. These results were achieved by: supporting 10 Municipal Councils in preventing the spread of the pandemic COVID-19 in Quelimane, Mocuba Guru&#xE9; (Zamb&#xE9;zia Province); Angoche, Malema (Nampula Province), Montepuez (Cabo Delgado Province), Lichinga, Metangula, Marrupa, Cuamba (Niassa Province); conducting an awareness campaign (via sms) for about 19. 877 market users about prevention measures; Sensitization of 51,662 market users to the use of electronic and mobile payment systems (IZI, Mpesa and Emola) through messages disseminated via megaphone and panels placed in the market vendors stalls.
o Through engagement with Voluntary Service Overseas (VSO) a webinar was developed on the contribution of volunteers fighting HIV and AIDS (1st December) and the inclusion of more vulnerable groups in all areas in the COVID19 Context; promoted the SDGs and put on the volunteers agenda; ditch cleaning and drainage in Mafalala; disseminated the Volunteer Law; Participation of National Volunteers in the Square of Heroes to recognize volunteers that contributed to the country even though they are no longer alive; held a fair for NGOs and CBOs and a workshop to promote and discuss the role of volunteers, their recognition and how they can be better supported; painted 8 schools (2 in each of the provinces, Manica, Sofala, Cabo Delgado and Nampula).</narrative>
      </comment>
